        <h1>Understanding Cataracts</h1>
        
        <section class="about-content">
            <p class="intro">
                A cataract is a clouding of the natural lens inside your eye. This process usually develops gradually over many years and can affect one or both eyes. Understanding cataracts is the first step toward making informed decisions about your eye health.
            </p>

            <h2>What is a Cataract?</h2>
            <p>
                The lens in your eye works much like a camera lens, focusing light onto the retina for clear vision. As you age, proteins in your lens can clump together, forming a cataract that clouds your vision. This is a natural part of aging, though other factors can accelerate its development.
            </p>

            <h2>Common Symptoms</h2>
            <ul class="qualifications-list">
                <li>Blurred or cloudy vision</li>
                <li>Difficulty seeing at night or in low light</li>
                <li>Sensitivity to light and glare</li>
                <li>Seeing "halos" around lights</li>
                <li>Fading or yellowing of colors</li>
                <li>Frequent changes in glasses or contact lens prescriptions</li>
                <li>Double vision in one eye</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Risk Factors</h2>
            <ul class="qualifications-list">
                <li>Advanced age</li>
                <li>Diabetes</li>
                <li>Prolonged exposure to sunlight</li>
                <li>Smoking</li>
                <li>Obesity</li>
                <li>High blood pressure</li>
                <li>Previous eye injury or inflammation</li>
                <li>Long-term use of corticosteroid medications</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Diagnosis</h2>
            <p>
                Cataract diagnosis involves a comprehensive eye examination, including:
            </p>
            <ul class="qualifications-list">
                <li>Visual acuity test</li>
                <li>Slit-lamp examination</li>
                <li>Retinal examination under dilation</li>
                <li>Tonometry (eye pressure test)</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Treatment Options</h2>
            <p>
                In the early stages, vision changes from cataracts can be managed with:
            </p>
            <ul class="qualifications-list">
                <li>New eyeglass prescriptions</li>
                <li>Anti-glare coatings on lenses</li>
                <li>Brighter lighting for reading and other activities</li>
                <li>Magnifying lenses for specific tasks</li>
            </ul>

            <p>
                When cataracts significantly affect your daily life, surgery is the only effective treatment. Modern cataract surgery is one of the safest and most successful surgical procedures performed today. During surgery, the clouded natural lens is removed and replaced with a clear artificial lens called an intraocular lens (IOL).
            </p>

